Here is a solution using an [`ActionBlock`][1] from the [TPL Dataflow library][2].

    class C&lt;T&gt;
    {
        private readonly ActionBlock&lt;T&gt; _actionBlock;

        public C(Action&lt;T&gt; action)
        {
            _actionBlock = new ActionBlock&lt;T&gt;(action);
        }

        public void Do(T item)
        {
            var accepted = _actionBlock.Post(item);
            Debug.Assert(accepted);
        }
    }

In this example the `Post` method will always accept the item, because the `ActionBlock` is unbounded. If you later decide to impose a limit to the number of items that may be buffered by the block ([`BoundedCapacity`][3] option), then you&#39;ll need to rethink how to handle the case when the limit has been reached. Using `SendAsync().Wait()` instead of `Post()` is one way of handling this.

The TPL Dataflow library is embedded in the Core platform. For .NET Framework you need [this package][4].

  [1]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.threading.tasks.dataflow.actionblock-1
  [2]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/standard/parallel-programming/dataflow-task-parallel-library
  [3]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.threading.tasks.dataflow.dataflowblockoptions.boundedcapacity
  [4]: https://www.nuget.org/packages/System.Threading.Tasks.Dataflow/

